04705nam a22006975i 9780824846398DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222009hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248463987 a10.1515/97808248463982doi  a(DE-B1597)570729  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aSB436b.R38 2009 7aGAR0240002bisacsh04a635.91 aRauch, Fred D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSmall Trees for the Tropical Landscape /cPaul R. Weissich, Fred D. Rauch. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b539 color illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSmall Trees for the Tropical Landscape -- tTailored Small Trees -- tAppendix A: Hawai‘i-Pacific Weed Risk Assessment Project -- tAppendix B: Small Trees for Windbreak or Screening -- tAppendix C: Small Trees for Coastal Gardens -- tAppendix D: Small Trees with Significant Flowers or Colored Fruit or Foliage -- tAppendix E: Small Trees with Edible Fruit or Leaves -- tAppendix F: Small Trees for Warm, Dry Environments -- tReferences -- tReferences -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past several decades, the U.S. cityscape has changed radically. Large areas have been cleared of natural vegetation to accommodate new development. The “urban forest,” which consists of all city trees, natural and planted, has been severely and negatively impacted. A 2003 study indicates that we are losing through clearing and grading four trees for every one planted. This is a wake-up call for greatly increased planting in the urban forest and the need to popularize small trees (defined as trees that grow up to thirty feet high) for diminished city spaces.Small Trees for the Tropical Landscape describes and illustrates 129 species and subspecies and 48 named varieties, cultivars, and forms plus 23 hybrids appropriate for the home garden and confined public landscape spaces. The authors have also included a section on “Tailored Small Trees,” large shrubs that are readily transformed into small trees through intelligent, selective pruning. They identify and describe 67 species and subspecies; 40 named varieties, cultivars, and forms; and 21 hybrids that are appropriate for this conversion.Several appendices will assist the gardener with tree selection for specific purposes (screens and windbreaks, coastal gardens, edible fruit, and colorful flowers and foliage). Species that may cause skin irritation or that are poisonous are identified in the text as are those trees with the ability to fix nitrogen. The authors also warn against planting a number of species known to be invasive in Hawai‘i and advise caution when planting others that have the potential to escape cultivation and become weeds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aOrnamental treeszTropics. 0aTrees in citieszTropics. 0aUrban forestryzUnited States. 7aGARDENING / Trees.2bisacsh1 aWeissich, Paul R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484639840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824846398423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824846398/original  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STM